Males of this species complex are associated with females based on locality as, in general, the two sexes are differently coloured (see 
Figs 5–9
) but one male from Chikkaballapur (
BMNH
) has the pronotum as in most females (
Fig. 9
). Despite the variation in colour the genitalia in males are similar but further studies on the observed slight variation in the aedeagal shaft are needed to elucidate the taxonomy. The aedeagus of the male (
Fig. 214
), collected in cop with the female (
Fig. 216
) (see Material examined, Calcutta museum compound (
BMNH
)) was noted (before loss) as similar to other males examined in the complex with a relatively narrow shaft in lateral view. Three female specimens from 
Assam
, Mishmi Hills (
BMNH
) could belong to this complex but are slightly longer (
5.8mm
) and have the pronotum completely orange-brown.
